=== BUG 1: Navbar wordmark becomes unreadable on scroll ===

The "VALE & MERCER" wordmark in components/Navbar.tsx has scroll-aware colour theming
(the `darkHeroPages` logic mentioned in the project audit) intended to keep it light
when over a dark hero image and dark when over a light background. On mobile, after
scrolling past the hero into a light/cream section (background colour ~#EFECE6, the
--c-bg token), the wordmark is still rendering in a light/gold tone and is nearly
invisible against the light background — see attached screenshot for exact symptom
(text visible but extremely low contrast against cream background while menu/burger
icon stays visibly dark, meaning the two elements are using inconsistent colour logic).

Investigate:
- How Navbar.tsx currently decides text colour (scroll position threshold? page-based
  darkHeroPages list? both?)
- Why this particular page/section triggers the wrong colour, or whether this happens
  site-wide
- Whether the colour switch is keyed off scroll Y position, or off which page you're on,
  or some combination, and whether that logic actually matches where light vs dark
  background sections actually are on each page

Fix it so the wordmark colour always has sufficient contrast against whatever is
actually behind it at the current scroll position, on every page, not just the
homepage. If the current implementation hardcodes per-page assumptions about where
dark/light sections are, make it more robust (e.g. driven by actual scroll position
relative to known section boundaries, or a CSS-based contrast solution like mix-blend-mode:
difference, whichever fits better with the existing MotionProvider/AtmosphereLayer
scroll-tied colour system already in place — check how AtmosphereLayer.tsx ties colour
to scrollYProgress and consider reusing that same source of truth so the navbar and
background never disagree).

